From 7a44410048773b1b48b0ec46751e34fe7504af53 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Alexandre Cordeiro <nenisdeno@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 21 May 2026 18:57:18 -0300
Subject: [PATCH] Add per-model max_completion_batch_size and prefill_step_size
 overrides

Extends the per-model knobs surface introduced by per_model_max_concurrent
with two more dicts on SchedulerConfig: per_model_max_completion_batch_size
and per_model_prefill_step_size. Same keying contract (basename or
fully-qualified model_name) and same resolution shape (lookup in
Scheduler.__init__ replaces the config field on the dedicated instance).

Why
===

Different model sizes saturate at different batch-fusion ceilings (3B-class
often happy at completion_batch_size=64 where 8B-class wants 16), and
prefill-chunk sweet-spots also differ (smaller models tolerate smaller
chunks for lower TTFT; larger models prefer bigger chunks). Operators
running heterogeneous models in one oMLX process need to tune these
per-model rather than carry one global compromise.

Touchpoints
===========

- omlx/settings.py: two new dict fields on SchedulerSettings;
  from_dict/to_dict round-trip; apply_args() parses
  --per-model-max-completion-batch-size and --per-model-prefill-step-size
  with the same shape as --per-model-max-concurrent;
  to_scheduler_config() propagates both dicts.
- omlx/cli.py: two new --per-model-... flags wired to argparse.
- omlx/scheduler.py: two new dict fields on SchedulerConfig; per-model
  lookup in Scheduler.__init__ that REPLACES the corresponding config
  field on the dedicated Scheduler instance (mirrors the existing
  per_model_max_concurrent block).
- tests/test_per_model_perf_knobs.py: round-trip + CLI parsing +
  propagation tests mirroring test_per_model_concurrency.py.

Composition
===========

* Pairs with --per-model-max-concurrent (already in this branch); the
  three knobs together cover the operationally-relevant per-model
  surface for heterogeneous-model deployments.
* Independent of the exception-safety + recovery patches; works at the
  scheduler-admission layer, not the Metal command-buffer layer.
